because obesity is a major driver of insulin resistance, a key mechanism in its development. Excess adipose tissue, particularly visceral fat, releases inflammatory cytokines and free fatty acids that impair insulin signaling in muscle, liver, and adipose tissues. This leads to reduced glucose uptake, increased hepatic glucose production, and compensatory hyperinsulinemia, eventually resulting in beta-cell dysfunction and type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddison\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an adrenal insufficiency disorder that is not directly associated with obesity. It is typically caused by autoimmune destruction of the adrenal glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraves\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune disorder that causes hyperthyroidism. While thyroid disorders can be associated with weight changes, Graves\u0027 disease is not directly linked to obesity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECushing\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by excessive cortisol production, which can lead to weight gain and obesity. However, it is not a complication of obesity itself but rather a separate endocrine disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoparathyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition characterised by low levels of parathyroid hormone, leading to hypocalcaemia. It is not associated with obesity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type 2 diabetes is a common endocrine complication of obesity due to insulin resistance caused by excess adipose tissue.","Visceral adipose tissue releases inflammatory cytokines and free fatty acids that impair insulin signaling.","Obesity-induced insulin resistance leads to reduced glucose uptake, increased hepatic glucose production, and compensatory hyperinsulinemia."],"references":["Klein S, Gastaldelli A, Yki-J\u00e4rvinen H, Scherer PE. Why does obesity cause diabetes? Cell Metab. 2022 Jan 4;34(1):11-20. doi: 10.1016/j.cmet.2021.12.012. PMID: 34986330; PMCID: PMC8740746.","Barnes AS. The epidemic of obesity and diabetes: trends and treatments. Tex Heart Inst J. 2011;38(2):142-4. PMID: 21494521; PMCID: PMC3066828.","Aras M, Tchang BG, Pape J. Obesity and Diabetes. Nurs Clin North Am. 2021 Dec;56(4):527-541. doi: 10.1016/j.cnur.2021.07.008. PMID: 34749892."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60506"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17928"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60506"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T20:08:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T20:09:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10642"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75000"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links